=EF=BB=BF<div class=3D"table">
	<h2 id=3D"tblSerialnumber" data-cy=3D"tblSerialnumber"><a href=3D"http://1=
0.10.201.22:81/Report/DatabaseDocumentation.aspx#toc" class=3D"tocref">=E2=
=87=A7</a>tblSerialnumber</h2>
	<p>This table stores the software serial numbers pulled from a Windows com=
puter's registry. The registry locations Lansweeper searches for keys can b=
e found in TsysSerials. Note that software serial numbers and software inst=
allations have nothing to do with each other. TblSerialnumber stores softwa=
re serial numbers; tblSoftware(Uni) stores software installations. These ta=
bles cannot be linked. Software installation scanning recreates Add/Remove =
Programs, while software serial scanning searches the registry for serial n=
umbers. It is perfectly possible for a serial to be left behind in the regi=
stry when the corresponding software package is uninstalled. If a serial is=
 stored in tblSerialnumber, it was found in the computer's registry. Lanswe=
eper isn=E2=80=99t saying that the corresponding software is installed on t=
he machine. It is saying that it found the software serial in the computer'=
s registry.</p>
